mosquito habitat mapper:comments: The area was identified was identified as a mostly dried up “puddle” formed at the basin of a dried up stream and was located near 3-4 similar puddles as well. Unlike the other nearby puddles, which were layered with a thin deposit of fat/oil, this puddle had several mosquito larvae and pupae developing within it as well as a larger quantity of algae and decaying leaves. Unfortunately, despite bringing my clip-on microscopic lens with me on my excursion, I was unable to acquire any viable images of the larvae and I was also unable to bring any samples back home with me for acquiring better images.

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This body of water is a 5-6 inch deep puddle formed at the bottom of a recently excavated hole created for the purpose of performing maintenance on a series of pipes used to transport water from my house to a nearby garden. Although this hole has been around for a few weeks and has had a considerable amount of water in it before, it was only within the last few days of consistent rainfall that female mosquitoes have been able to lay eggs in this hole with a guarantee that they would hatch before the water would evaporate or be soaked into the ground. No algae was found in the hole and there were very few areas in this puddle to provide shade for the larvae, but nonetheless, a large population of these larvae were able to survive thanks to their diet of deceased insects and decaying leaves that had also ended up in the water they were raised in. After further analysis and research, I was able to identify it as being either Aedes albopictus or Aedes aegyptii. Afterwards, I used a bucket to remove as much water and mosquito larvae as I could until a very minuscule amount of water and larvae remained (these larvae will quite unlikely reach the pupal or adult stages of their lives due to the water’s quickly decreasing volume and quickly increasing temperature).

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This body of water is a small, plastic bucket initially used for temporarily holding freshly cut flowers and keeping them hydrated with water during their transportation. At some point recently, the container was discarded and left in a shady place near a garden where it then would fill up with rainwater and become a suitable habitat for mosquito larvae. After further research and macroscopic imaging, I later determined that this well-matured mosquito larvae most likely belonged to the Aedes genus as either albopictus or aegyptii.

mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is one of the seven mosquito traps that I created as to gather information about the oviposition deterrent effects of certain plants against local mosquito species in my area. This specific trap is labeled as “control #1,” which has no mosquito repelling plants surrounding it. The trap contains and a large quantity of decaying grass, leaves, and lake water and a large population of about 200 individual mosquito larvae. After closer analysis, it was determined that the mosquito species identified are most likely of the genus Culex.

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is one of the seven traps that I created to gather information on the effectiveness of the oviposition deterrent effects of several different mosquito repelling plants that I am using in my experiment. This trap is labeled as “trap #3,” the lavender trap, which is filled with lake water and decaying leaves and grass, and contained a small population of mosquito larvae. Due to the specimens large size, I was unable to get any clear images of the specimen’s full body, however, based upon my research, I believe that this specimen may belong to the genus Culex due to its hairy body and wide abdomen.

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is one of the seven traps that I created to evaluate the effectiveness of the oviposition deterrent effects of different mosquito repellent plants on mosquito species local to my area. This trap is labeled as “trap #1,” the geranium trap, and is filled with decaying leaves and grass, as well as rainwater. Previously, I had not noticed any mosquito larvae in this tire trap, however, as of today I was able to identify exactly one mosquito larvae specimen in the tire that had gone unnoticed last time I checked. The physiology of this larvae specimen was consistent with that of the physical characteristics of the same exact mosquito larvae that I found in my lavender trap the day before last (meaning that it is most likely of the genus Culex). However, due to the fact that only one was spotted, this would mean that the specimen observed is not a mosquito larvae, but instead some other form of aquatic insect larvae (as most mosquitoes produce young hundreds at time). I then came to the conclusion that this was indeed a mosquito larvae and that all other larvae but this one specimen had most likely been consumed by some predator.

mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is one of the seven mosquito traps that I have created for the purpose of testing the effectiveness of the oviposition deterrent effects of different mosquito repellent plants on mosquito species local to my area. This trap is labeled as “trap #1,” the geranium trap, and is filled with decaying leaves and grass, as well as lake water. This trap did indeed contain mosquito larvae, however, only one individual larvae was observed. After further investigation, I was unable to identify the exact species nor the genus of this specimen. Due to the lack of of other mosquito larvae in this trap, it would likely lead one to believe that other larvae also existed in this trap at one point but were most likely consumed by predators (this would be suggested by the fact that most mosquitoes often tend to lay between 100 and 200 eggs at a time). The large size and dark coloration of this specimen, however, has caused me much trouble and confusion due to the fact that this species does not appear to registered in the GlobeObserver database.

mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is one of the seven mosquito larvae traps that I created as to gather information on the effectiveness of several different mosquito repellent plants and their effects as oviposition deterrents for mosquito species local to my area. This trap is labeled as “trap #4,” the lemon balm trap, which is surrounded by lemon balm plants and is filled with decaying leaves and grass and a large quantity of lake water. This trap also contains a large population of mosquito larvae with a count of approximately 150 individuals. However, I was unable to collect and identify any specimens and determine the exact species.

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is one of the seven mosquito traps that I have created for the purpose of testing the effectiveness of the oviposition deterrent effects of different mosquito repellent plants on mosquito species local to my area. This trap is labeled as “trap #2,” the lemon grass trap, which is filled with decaying leaves and grass, as well as lake water. Approximately 15-20 mosquito larvae were observed in this trap. The mosquito larvae observed were large in size, dark in color, and all appeared to have reached their 3rd or 4th instar. However, due to their large size and dark color, I was highly unsure as to exactly what species this mosquito larvae belonged to (and for a second, if it was a mosquito larvae at all). As a result, I was unable to match the larvae with any species found in the GlobeObserver database.

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This body of water was located near a concrete storm drain and had a reasonable amount of water, algae and plants within it. Around 5 mosquito larvae and 2 mosquito pupae were identified and I made an attempt to capture some to bring back home for identification. Despite my efforts at capturing the larvae and pupae, I was low on time and proper field equipment, and after several minutes of trying to hunt down the mosquitoes with my small plastic pipette and sample container the mosquito specimens got the best of me with their speed and hiding abilities before I had the chance to acquire any.

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This small body of standing freshwater was identified as a drainage ditch located next to a inlet of water from Lake Grapevine in a nearby neighborhood. This body of water was overpopulated with L. minor (common duckweed) and therefore made observation of potential mosquito larvae nearly impossible. However, after sifting through the water for some time, I found several mosquito larvae molts which led me to believe that there likely are (or recently was) a large population of mosquito larvae inhabiting this ditch underneath the layer of duckweed.

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is a drainage ditch that goes though a concrete underpass next to a quiet street in a nearby neighborhood. The site contained several pond snails, diving beetles, and a large population of mosquito larvae. Upon analysis of the larvae specimens that I had gathered, I came to the conclusion that this species of mosquito is most likely Aedes albopictus (as the specimen’s pointed comb scales would suggest).

mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This body of water is a drainage ditch found next to a quiet road in a nearby neighborhood. The ditch passes though a concrete underpass built beneath the neighborhood’s main road and contains brown (but not murky) water, rocks, and debris/detritus, as well as a fauna such as diving beetles, tubifex worms, pond snails, and even some bullfrogs nearby. However, to my surprise, this site also contained a number of mosquito larvae of varying sizes (most of which appeared to be nearing the pupal stage of their life cycle). Throughout analysis of the mosquito larvae, I was led to believe that this particular specimen was of the genus Culex, but upon further microscopic imaging and comparison of specimen characteristics to several identification databases, I found that this mosquito species is most likely some form of Aedes species (more specifically, Aedes aegyptii as stated by the Globe Observer identification system).

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This body of water is a small, murky pond with an abundance of water plants to provide shade and nursery areas for developing mosquito larvae. However, after taking a number of water samples from the sites, no mosquito larvae found to be present. Despite the seemingly hospitable loving conditions provided for mosquito larvae, a probable answer to their absence most likely lies in the fact that the pond itself was stocked with red-eared slider turtles and number of freshwater fish of varying sizes (both of which I would believe to be predators of mosquito larvae and pupae).

mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This body of water is a pond located near a local freeway and has little shade and plant coverage, therefore making it a very unlikely home for mosquito larvae, hence why none were seen. However, this does not mean that mosquitoes are not present at site.

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is characterized as a ditch located on the side of a wide road in a residential area. The surface water of the ditch had recently been coated with a thin layer of grass as a result of periodical landscaping. Although no mosquito larvae were identified at the site (likely as a result of too much direct sunlight) I would imagine that the fresh grass shavings should greatly reduce the average sustained sunlight across the ditch while also providing an abundance of food and debris for which future generations of mosquito larvae may enjoy and utilize to thrive.

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is a drainage ditch connected to a concrete drainage underpass that I have already visited a few weeks prior. Although no mosquitoes were found to be present at the location of the site, my initial thoughts were that after about a week or two, the water would become more suitable for sustaining mosquitoes and that larvae would soon develop. However, to my surprise, no larvae were observed on my second visit to the site. Instead, I was greeted by the sight of many longear sunfish of varying sizes. I believe that the presence of these fish would most likely indicate the reason why no mosquito larvae have been found at this location yet.

Because of this, it is quite unlikely that mosquitoes spawn in such an environment.

mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This body of water is characterized as a small drainage ditch connected to a concrete storage drain. Several regions of the site were scattered with growths of filamentous algae and water plants as well as a high abundance of tadpoles, big and small. Due to predation, it is most likely that any mosquito larvae that previously lived in this ditch were killed off by their tadpole predators. In conclusion, it is likely that if there are any mosquito larvae located at this site, all existing specimens would have been too small to observe in the field and they likely will not survive to reach the pupal stage for as long as the tadpoles remain.

mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is a small well formed in what is believed to be a a shallow/clogged drainage pipe in the middle of a sidewalk near Georgetown university. This site itself covers a minuscule area, but is believed to be much deeper and contains a large quantity of debris and decaying leaf matter. No mosquito larvae were observed.

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is a large puddle that had recently developed as a result of heavy rainfall from earlier this week in the Baltimore area. The body of water is located in a construction site, and as it is only temporary, it is unlikely that It could become a sustainable mosquito habitat.

org_name: United States of America Citizen Science
mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is located in an area where heavy construction is under way and where much water has built up as a result of heavy rainfall earlier in the week. No mosquito larvae were observed. However, a large quantity of algae and numerous water-bugs found at the site would prove that this body of stagnant water may have been here for longer and may or may not be a suitable habitat for mosquito larvae.

mosquito habitat mapper:comments: This site is a small freshwater pond located in Ithaca, New York. The site was populated with many different species of aquatic and terrestrial plants as well as a number of animals such as ducks, frogs, and dragonflies (suggesting that mosquitoes and mosquito larvae would most likely be predated upon by hungry insectivores, rendering the site as mostly or entirely devoid of mosquito life). No mosquito larvae were observed.
